      <exercise xml:id="ez-mv_deriv-limits-try-line">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the function <m>h</m> defined by <m>h(x,y) = \frac{2x^2y}{x^4 + y^2}.</m>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the domain of <m>h</m>?
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate the limit of <m>h</m> at <m>(0,0)</m> along all linear paths the contain the origin. What does this tell us about <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m>? (Hint: A non-vertical line throught the origin has the form <m> y = mx </m> for some constant <m>m</m>.)
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Does <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m> exist? Verify your answer. Check by using appropriate technology to sketch both surface and contour plots of <m>h</m> near <m>(0,0)</m>.  Write several sentences to say how your plots affirm your findings about <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                As a rational function,
                <m>h</m> is defined everywhere except at the points where the denominator is 0.
                Since <m>x^4 + y^2 = 0</m> only when <m>x=y=0</m>,
                the domain of <m>g</m> is all ordered pairs <m>(x,y)</m> not equal to <m>(0,0)</m>,
                or the <m>x</m>-<m>y</m> plane with the origin removed.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Along the non-vertical path <m>y=mx</m> we have
                <me>
                  f(x,mx) = \frac{2x^2(mx) }{x^4 + (mx)^2} = \frac{2mx^3}{x^4 + m^2 x^2} = \frac{2mx^3}{x^2 (1 + m^2)} = \frac{2mx}{1 + m^2}
                </me>,
                so
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(x,mx) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2mx}{1 + m^2} = 0
                </me>.
                Additionally, along the vertical line <m>x=0</m> we have 
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(0,y) = \lim_{y \to 0} \frac{0}{y^2} =  0
                </me>.  
                So <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y) = 0</m> along all linear paths that contain the origin.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                No, <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m> does not exist. From our work above it seems that <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m> may be 0. However, consider the limit along the path <m>y=x^2</m>. We have 
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(x,x^2) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2x^2(x^2) }{x^4 + (x^2)^2} = \frac{2x^4}{x^4 + x^4} = \frac{2x^4}{2x^4} = 1
                </me>. 
                Since the limits along different paths are not equal, the limit does not exist. On a surface plot of <m>h(x, y)</m> we can see that along the <m>x</m>-axis and the <m>y</m>-axis (excluding the origin) the value of <m>h</m> is 0, while along the curve <m>y=x^2</m> (excluding the origin) the value of <m>h</m> is 1. On CalcPlot3D the top of the graph looks somewhat jagged rather than smooth. On the contour plots, contours associated with different function values all approach the origin, indicating that near the origin the function takes on different values. This also provides evidence that the limit does not exist. (GRAPHS NEEDED HERE?)
                
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>


        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                As a rational function,
                <m>h</m> is defined everywhere except at the points where the denominator is 0.
                Since <m>x^4 + y^2 = 0</m> only when <m>x=y=0</m>,
                the domain of <m>g</m> is all ordered pairs <m>(x,y)</m> not equal to <m>(0,0)</m>,
                or the <m>x</m>-<m>y</m> plane with the origin removed.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Along the non-vertical path <m>y=mx</m> we have
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(x,mx) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2x^2(mx) }{x^4 + (mx)^2} = \lim_{x \to 0}  \frac{2mx^3}{x^4 + m^2 x^2} = \lim_{x \to 0}  \frac{2mx^3}{x^2 (1 + m^2)} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2mx}{1 + m^2} = 0
                </me>.
                Additionally, along the vertical line <m>x=0</m> we have 
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} f(0,y) = \lim_{y \to 0} \frac{0}{y^2} =  0
                </me>.  
                So <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y) = 0</m> along all linear paths that contain the origin.
