      <exercise xml:id="Ez_10_1_4">
        <statement>
          <p>
            For each of the following prompts, provide an example of a function of two variables with the desired properties (with justification), or explain why such a function does not exist.
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  A function <m>p</m> that is defined at <m>(0,0)</m>, but <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} p(x,y)</m> does not exist.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  A function <m>q</m> that does not have a limit at <m>(0,0)</m>, but that has the same limiting value along any line <m>y = mx</m> as <m>x \to 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  A function <m>r</m> that is continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>, but <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} r(x,y)</m> does not exist.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  A function <m>s</m> such that
                  <me>
                    \lim_{(x,x) \to (0,0)} s(x,x) = 3 \ \ \ \mbox{and}  \ \ \ \lim_{(x,2x) \to (0,0)} s(x,2x) = 6,
                  </me>
                  for which  <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} s(x,y)</m> exists.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  A function <m>t</m> that is not defined at <m>(1,1)</m> but <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (1,1)} t(x,y)</m> does exist.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>


        <answer>
          <p>
            Many possible answers. The following are examples.
          </p>

          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>p(x,y) = \frac{2x+y}{x+y}</m> if
                <m>(x,y) \neq (0,0)</m> and <m>p(0,0) = 0</m>.
                So <m>p</m> is defined at <m>(0,0)</m> by definition.
                Note that
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} p(0,y) = \lim_{y \to 0} \frac{y}{y} = 1
                </me>
                but
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} p(x,0) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2x}{x} = 2
                </me>,
                so <m>p</m> does not have a limit at <m>(0,0)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>q(x,y) = \frac{x^2y}{x^4+y^2}</m>as in <xref ref="act-mv_deriv-limits-parabloa">Activity</xref>.
                Along the line <m>y=mx</m> we have
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} q(x,mx) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{mx^3}{x^2(x^2+m^2)} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{mx}{x^2+m^2} = 0
                </me>,
                so <m>q</m> has the same limiting value along any line <m>y = mx</m> as <m>x \to 0</m>.
                However,
                <me>
                  \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} q(x,x^2) = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{x^4}{2x^4} = \frac{1}{2}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By definition, if <m>r</m> is continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>,
                then <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} r(x,y)</m> exists and is equal to <m>r(0,0)</m>.
                So there is no such function.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The first limit is the same as
                <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} s(x,y) = 3</m> along the path <m>y=x</m> and the second is
