      <exercise xml:id="Ez_10_1_5">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the properties of continuity to determine the set of points at which each of the following functions is continuous. Justify your answers. 
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>f</m> defined by <m>f(x,y) = \frac{x+2y}{x-y}</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>g</m> defined by <m>g(x,y) = \frac{\sin(x)}{1+e^y}</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>h</m> defined by 
                  <me>h(x,y) = \begin{cases} \frac{xy}{x^2+y^2} \amp \text{ if } (x,y) \neq (0,0)  \\ 0 \amp \text{ if } (x,y) = (0,0) \end{cases}</me>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>k</m> defined by 
                  <me>k(x,y) = \begin{cases} \frac{x^2y^4}{x^2+y^2} \amp \text{ if } (x,y) \neq (0,0)  \\ 0 \amp \text{ if } (x,y) = (0,0) \end{cases}</me>
                </p>
              </li>

            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  The function <m>f</m> is undefined with <m>x-y=0</m>, so it is not continuous along the line <m>y=x</m>. It is continuous everywhere else since it is the quotient of continuous functions.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Here the denominator is never 0, so the function <m>g</m> is continuous everywhere since it is the quotient of two continuous functions.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  While <m>h</m> is defined at <m>(0, 0)</m>, we found in <xref ref="Ez_10_1_2">Exercise</xref> that <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m> does not exist. Thus <m>h</m> is not continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>. At all other points it is continuous because it is a quotient of continuous functions.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  At all points other than <m>(0, 0)</m> the function <m>k</m> is continuous because it is the quotient of continuous functions. Taking <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y)</m> along linear paths through the origin and along the path <m>y = x^n</m> yields 0. We can prove that <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y) = 0</m> by using the Squeeze Theorem, and so <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y) = k (0, 0)</m>. Thus <m>k</m> is continuous everywhere.
                </p>
              </li>

            </ol>
          
        </answer>


