              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Here the denominator is never 0, so the function <m>g</m> is continuous everywhere since it is the quotient of two continuous functions.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                While <m>h</m> is defined at <m>(0, 0)</m>, we found in <xref ref="Ez_10_1_2">Exercise</xref> that <m>\lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} h(x,y)</m> does not exist. Thus <m>h</m> is not continuous at <m>(0,0)</m>. At all other points it is continuous because it is a quotient of continuous functions.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                At all points other than <m>(0, 0)</m> the function <m>k</m> is continuous because it is the quotient of continuous functions. Taking <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y)</m> along linear paths through the origin and along the path <m>y = x^n</m> yields 0.
              </p>  
                
              <p>
                We use the Squeeze Theorem to prove that <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y) = 0</m>. Note that
                <me>
                   \frac{x^2y^4}{x^2 + y^2} = \left (\frac{x^2}{x^2 + y^2} \right ) y^4 \leq y^4,
                </me>
                so
                <me>
                  0 \leq  \frac{x^2y^4}{x^2 + y^2}  \leq y^4
                </me>.
                Since <m>y^4 \to 0</m> as <m>y \to 0</m>, by Squeeze Theorem <m>\frac{x^2y^4}{x^2 + y^2} \to 0</m> as <m>(x, y) \to (0,0)</m>. Thus <m> \lim_{(x,y) \to (0,0)} k(x,y) = k(0,0)</m> and so <m>k</m> is continuous at <m>(0, 0)</m>.
